2026-04-21 01:40:31 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module – light‑sensor / comparator circuit', 'control (ambient sensor) module – timing/sensitivity feedback network around the relay driver'] hypothesis_explanation='All supply rails from the battery through the relay contacts to the load module are stable at about 11.8–11.9 V with correct polarity, and the protection diode plus both lamps in the load module behave normally and show steady voltage during operation. Continuity measurements to the main lamp are simply showing the combined resistance of the two parallel lamps and wiring, not an intermittent open.\n\nMultiple tests that exercised the timing potentiometer, sensitivity potentiometer, and light sensor input all returned the same meta‑result: the circuit simulator reports non‑convergence and an unstable or oscillating state, while the relay terminals sit at roughly the same DC level on both sides. This is consistent with a control‑loop instability or oscillation in the analog front‑end (sensor/comparator and its RC timing network) that intermittently drives the relay into a brief off state approximately every 20 seconds, causing the 0.5 s lamp outages.\n\nBecause the power supply module and load module (diode and lamps) have been effectively cleared, the remaining credible root cause is a fault internal to the control module’s light‑sensor/comparator/timing network (for example, an incorrect or drifting component value, defective op‑amp/comparator, or mis‑biased feedback path) that makes the relay‑drive node oscillate or chatter at a very low frequency independent of external light changes. Replacing or repairing the control module’s sensor/comparator and associated timing/sensitivity network should eliminate the periodic lamp turn‑offs.'
