2026-04-21 01:41:10 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['main lamp in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='All wiring, connectors, supply rails, the protection diode, and the control (ambient sensor) module (including relay and its drive circuitry) have been tested and show stable voltages and solid continuity with no polarity errors. The brief 0.5 s outages persist with a steady ~11–12 V present at the load‑module input and across the lamp/indicator nodes, and the control relay contacts remain effectively closed. This localizes the fault to the load element itself rather than upstream circuitry.\n\nContinuity measurements from each main‑lamp terminal back to the respective load input cables show ~97–99 Ω in each leg, implying a total series resistance on the order of 200 Ω in the lamp path, which is abnormally high for a 12 V lamp that should draw significant current. Yet the lamps still light, indicating a partially degraded or intermittently opening filament/connection internal to the main lamp assembly (or its immediate socket) that can sustain conduction most of the time but occasionally drops enough current to extinguish the visible lamp briefly while the measured node voltages, dominated by the meter’s high impedance, remain near supply.\n\nGiven that all other components and interconnections have been ruled out by direct tests or previous replacement, the most plausible remaining root cause is an intermittent internal failure of the main lamp in the load module (e.g., cracked filament, internal contact, or high‑resistance joint). Replacing the main lamp assembly should restore continuous operation and eliminate the 20‑second, 0.5 s flicker.'
