2026-04-21 01:41:21 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['internal indicator lamp in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='All supply rails from battery through power and control modules are stable at ~11.8–12 V, with correct polarity and solid low‑resistance connections. The control module relay contacts remain effectively closed; tests show no intermittent opening or chattering at the ~20 s period. The diode into the load module is good and forward‑biased with a normal 0.7–0.8 V drop, and continuity from the load input posts into the load lamp network is on the order of 97–99 Ω, not intermittent. \n\nThe main lamp itself has already been replaced/verified and is not faulty. Yet the brief 0.5 s outages still occur and the simulator repeatedly reports an unstable or oscillating state, even though the measured DC voltages at the lamp and indicator nodes remain near 11 V. This strongly suggests the interruption is not in the main supply path, but within the parallel load branch that is not yet replaced: the internal indicator lamp.\n\nIf the internal indicator lamp has an intermittent filament or internal fault, its resistance could momentarily go very high or open every ~20 s as it heats/cools, perturbing the simulated load and causing the solver to flag non‑convergence while the main lamp, in parallel, still sees essentially the same node voltage. The brief effective open or rapid resistance change of this indicator branch can produce the observed flicker of the overall load without showing up as a conventional open in static continuity tests on the main lamp network.\n\nGiven that all upstream circuitry and the main lamp have been ruled out by targeted tests and prior unsuccessful repairs, the remaining plausible single‑component root cause in the load module is the internal indicator lamp. Replacing this component should eliminate the intermittent behavior and restore stable operation.'
