2026-04-21 01:42:01 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module – series wiring / internal resistance causing supply droop under dynamic load'] hypothesis_explanation='All module polarities and connectors are correct, and every sub‑component tested (lamps, load‑module diode, control‑module comparator/network, relay and its output node, connectors between modules) behaves nominally with stable ~11.8–12 V present right up to the load module input and across the lamps. Continuity from the lamps back to the load inputs is around 97–99 Ω, which is consistent with the expected load resistance, not an intermittent open. The relay contact is not opening or chattering, and the control output node stays steady when measured. The only remaining element that can periodically disturb the whole circuit without showing as a static voltage fault at the measurement points is the effective series resistance or wiring within the power‑supply module: a marginal internal connection or excessive series resistance that, under the specific dynamic interaction of battery, control electronics, and lamp load, allows the supply to momentarily droop enough to extinguish the lamp about every 20 s for ~0.5 s, while the green PSU LED (with much smaller current) stays lit and DC measurements averaged over time still look normal. Therefore the root cause is a fault in the power‑supply module’s internal series wiring / effective resistance, not in the downstream control or load components.'
