2026-04-21 01:42:13 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['wiring between power supply module and control (ambient sensor) module – fast‑connection terminals / cable pair'] hypothesis_explanation='All active components and internal circuits of the three modules have been effectively cleared:\n- Power‑supply battery and internal wiring hold a steady 12 V with no droop.\n- Control module input rails, internal decoupling, comparator/relay drive, relay coil, relay contacts, and the switched‑cables indicator branch all show a stable ~11.8–11.9 V, with the relay closed continuously.\n- Load‑module diode, main lamp, internal indicator lamp, and their wiring to the load‑module input posts show correct voltage and continuity, and replacing those parts had no effect.\n- The connectors and wiring between the control‑module output and load‑module input have been tested and show low resistance and correct polarity.\n\nThe only remaining plausible fault location consistent with the symptom—brief 0.5 s outages of the lamp every ~20 s while the PSU LED stays on and the control relay output node remains at ~11.85 V—is an intermittent or resistive connection on the *input* side of the control module: the fast‑connection terminals / cable pair joining the power‑supply module outputs to the control‑module inputs. \n\nIn this scenario, the battery and PSU LED remain powered because the fault is downstream of them, the control module experiences momentary supply interruption or series resistance sufficient for the lamp (through the closed relay) to extinguish, and the simulator reports an unstable or non‑converging state as the control module supply bounces. Because we never explicitly verified continuity of this particular connector pair under mechanical stress, and every other module and connector pair has been checked or replaced, the most consistent root cause is a faulty or intermittent connection in the wiring/fast‑connection terminals between the power supply module and the control (ambient sensor) module.'
