2026-04-21 01:42:24 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module – switched‑cables indicator LED and its series resistor path'] hypothesis_explanation='All primary power‑path components have been verified good: battery, PSU wiring, control‑module supply rails, relay contacts/coil drive, output cables to the load, load‑module diode, main lamp, and internal indicator lamp all show stable ~11.8–12 V with proper polarity and no droops or contact intermittence. The relay output node itself remains solid at ~11.85 V, and the relay never opens during the brief lamp outages. So the 0.5 s dark intervals cannot be due to the control path intentionally interrupting the 12 V supply.\n\nThe simulation consistently reports a non‑convergent / oscillating state specifically when probing nodes inside the control module, even though the physical relay state and lamp voltages are steady. This strongly suggests a small auxiliary branch inside the control module that is not part of the main relay path is interacting with the simulator and the load node. The only remaining untested element in that area is the ‘switched‑cables indicator’ LED branch that is tied from the relay‑output node (control output positive) through a series resistor to the control‑module ground.\n\nIf that indicator LED or its series resistor path is faulty—e.g., partially shorted, intermittently shorting, or mis‑valued—it could momentarily shunt significant current from the output node to ground every ~20 s as the internal sensor/comparator biases change. Because the relay contact and main wiring are low‑resistance, the resulting brief overload would drop the effective voltage seen by the lamp enough for it to extinguish for ~0.5 s, yet all static DC measurements taken outside those instants still appear near‑normal. The simulator’s non‑convergence flags during tests on the control module further support an abnormal nonlinear load at this node.\n\nAll other plausible fault locations have either been directly replaced (and found good) or exhaustively tested with no anomalies. Therefore the most likely remaining single‑point cause of the observed periodic 0.5 s lamp outages is a fault in the ambient sensor module’s switched‑cables indicator LED and its series resistor path, which should be repaired or replaced as a unit.'
