2026-04-21 01:42:40 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module – relay contacts (switched cable pair)'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show a solid 12 V supply from the power module through the control module output node to the load‑module input, with correct polarity and no droop. The control relay coil appears continuously energized (same potential on both terminals, relay output node at ~11.85 V), so upstream sensor/comparator circuitry is not intermittently opening the relay. The load‑module diode and both lamps test good, and continuity from lamp terminals to the load‑module input cables is stable. Yet the symptom remains a brief 0.5 s loss of light every ~20 s while the simulator reports oscillation.\n\nThis combination points to an intermittent open occurring right at the switching element that connects the control‑module output cables to the load path: the relay contacts themselves. A high‑resistance or contaminated contact can momentarily go open or significantly increase resistance under steady coil drive without affecting measured DC node voltages upstream, especially when probed at relatively slow sampling or on nodes that remain nominal while the actual contact interface drops out.\n\nSince sensor/comparator, timing network, indicator LED branch, battery, wiring, lamps, and series protection diode have all been ruled out by repair attempts and tests, the remaining credible root cause that fits the periodic brief outages is a faulty relay contact set in the ambient sensor module (the switched cable pair), intermittently opening despite the coil remaining energized.'
