2026-04-21 01:42:52 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['stacking / physical arrangement of modules causing intermittent optical feedback on ambient light sensor'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements show a stable 12 V supply from battery to load, correct polarity on all cable pairs, low‑resistance connections, and healthy components in the power‑supply, control, and load circuits. The relay output node remains solid at ~11.85 V, and both main and indicator lamps see a steady ~11 V across them even when the observed 0.5 s flicker occurs. Multiple hypotheses about specific components (relay, comparator, LEDs, wiring, lamp, diode, PSU droop, etc.) have been explicitly ruled out by replacement attempts that had no effect.\n\nThe remaining consistent explanation is that the apparent 20 s periodic on/off behavior is not caused by any electrical fault but by the physical configuration: the modules are stacked vertically with the load lamp on the top module and the ambient light sensor in the middle module. Light from the lamp can intermittently illuminate the sensor through panel gaps or reflections, causing the control loop to hover near its threshold and periodically switch or drive the simulator into a non‑convergent/oscillatory state, even though the relay contact remains effectively closed and the measured DC levels appear steady. Small environmental changes (e.g., movement, reflections, or heating) on a ~20 s time constant can modulate this optical feedback.\n\nThus the root cause is an installation/arrangement issue: the stacking and optical coupling between the lamp and the ambient light sensor create an unintended feedback path that leads to the observed periodic flicker and simulation instability, despite all components themselves being sound.'
