2026-04-21 01:43:01 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module – fast‑connection terminals / cable pair between its two faces (internal swapped polarity)'] hypothesis_explanation='All active components and external wiring have tested good: the battery and power‑supply output are stable, the relay coil is constantly driven, the relay contacts and external control‑to‑load connectors have low resistance and correct polarity, the series protection diode and both lamps in the load module are good, and the measured voltages at the control output node and load input remain at about 11.8 V/0 V even when the lamp briefly turns off.\n\nThe remaining plausible fault consistent with:\n• correct polarity at the battery, PSU output, control input, and control‑to‑load external connectors,\n• a constantly powered relay with output node at ~11.8 V,\n• the simulator repeatedly reporting a non‑convergent / oscillating state with no identifiable component failure,\n• and brief, regular 0.5 s dropouts of the lamp,\n\nis a configuration error internal to the control module: the two internal cable pairs (one to each face of the module) are cross‑connected such that the nominal + and − conductors between the relay contacts and the external output terminals are swapped or mis‑routed.\n\nThis internal polarity/cross‑connection fault would not show up in continuity tests across each external connector pair (they remain low‑ohmic) and would keep all individual components healthy, yet it can create an unintended feedback or reference loop inside the ambient sensor module that drives the simulator into an unstable, oscillatory state while periodically disturbing the load current seen at the lamp, causing the regular 20‑second, 0.5‑second flicker.\n\nTherefore, I hypothesize that the fault lies in the internal fast‑connection / cable routing between the two faces of the control (ambient sensor) module, effectively swapping polarity or mis‑wiring the switched cable pair inside that module rather than in any discrete component.'
