2026-04-21 01:43:13 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module – internal common reference / ground node connection between the two lamp branches and the load input negative cable'] hypothesis_explanation='All active components and wiring up to and including the control‑module relay output and the load‑module input have been tested and behave normally, with correct polarity and stable ~11.8–12 V supply. The main and indicator lamps themselves, as well as the series protection diode, have also been replaced/tested and found good. The relay contacts are confirmed closed and solid, and no wiring or connector intermittency exists between modules.\n\nVoltage measurements inside the load module show the positive side of both lamps at ~11.06 V and their negative side at ~0.05 V relative to the load‑module internal ground, and these readings are essentially identical for both lamps. Continuity tests from the lamp terminals back to the Load Input (+) and (−) cables show about 97–99 Ω in each leg, indicating that the resistance observed is dominated by the lamp filaments and that both positive and negative legs are indeed connected through the load module’s internal circuitry.\n\nGiven that:\n- The control output node remains solid at ~11.85 V with no drop during the 0.5 s outages.\n- The load‑module input cables see the same stable ~11.8–11.9 V.\n- The lamps extinguish briefly even though upstream voltages remain steady, and all previously suspected active components are verified good.\n\nThe only remaining plausible single‑point failure that can intermittently remove effective current from both parallel lamp branches without showing up as an upstream voltage change is a fault in the internal common reference/ground node of the load module: specifically, the connection that ties the lamp return nodes to the Load Input Cable (−) and to the module’s internal ground reference used for measurements. If this node goes intermittently high‑impedance or partially disconnected under certain conditions, the meter—referenced to internal ground—can still report near‑normal voltages, while the actual return path for lamp current opens momentarily, causing the 0.5 s outages. This fits the symptom that the simulator reports an unstable or oscillating state with no clear component‑level failure elsewhere.\n\nTherefore, the most likely root cause is a defective or mis‑wired internal ground/return connection within the load module between the lamp return nodes and the Load Input (−) terminal. Repairing or reworking this common reference/ground node should restore continuous lamp operation.'
