2026-04-21 01:43:22 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module – relay coil drive supply / reference (relay coil not actually energised though contacts are assumed closed)'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage and continuity tests show a solid 12 V from the battery through the power supply, through the control module’s output node, through the series diode, and right to both lamps. The load lamps and their wiring, the protection diode, all inter‑module connectors, and the supply wiring have been verified or even ‘repaired’ without effect. Despite the simulator reporting an “unstable or oscillating state,” every direct measurement at the relay output node, at the control module rails, and at the load input shows a stable DC level (~11.8 V). The brief 0.5 s extinguishing of the lamp occurs while the control module’s measured output remains high and the relay contacts are reported as good. The only remaining plausible explanation, consistent with all tests and past wrong hypotheses, is that the relay coil itself is never actually being driven/energised by the control circuit, i.e. the module is effectively wired so that the lamp path is always directly connected (bypassing the designed switching action), and what is interpreted as 20‑s control‑loop switching is in fact an artefact of the simulation/measurement around the un‑energised relay coil reference. This makes the system behave as if the relay were permanently closed, and the perceived periodic flicker must therefore be due to how the relay coil drive supply/reference is connected (or not) rather than any of the previously tested elements. Repairing the coil drive supply/reference so that the relay truly operates as intended would remove the apparent instability and the spurious 0.5 s lamp outages.'
